    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2742922">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2742922">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2742922)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2742922">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="2303803"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1486573693 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Feb 2017 17:08</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2742922">
									

<p>This is <em>super</em> gross, which I absolutely don't have a problem with in Foundationverse canon, but it's setting up a <em>lot</em> of irregular/never-before-seen types of events relating to 173's nature and not giving any ounce of explanation or backstory<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-445083-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-445083-1')">1</a></sup> for said events. This leaves me with two results after reading: squicked out, and confused about setting and context. I find myself wondering why and how 173 could be a human in a cask, and wondering about the logistics and function too; how and why does it snap necks when it's stuck like this? If people are feeding it&#8230; dead bodies, I inferred (or is it just chunks of random meat and body parts?) then why does it do what it does? If this is the only way the guy inside can live, then one would infer that &#8212; since feeding him isn't in the article's containment procedures &#8212; he would be dead in containment. Unless we're supposed to infer that he's eating the people he kills when he snaps necks, but again, that doesn't happen in containment enough for him to still be animate/alive.</p>
<p>The infamous blood and shit on the floor of the containment chamber was explained well and was worth its weight in body horror, but the rest doesn't quite make sense to me. I'm left wondering about additional context and backstory, but in a 'this feels incomplete in relation to how much new material it suggests' rather than a 'whoa, that was ominous' way. It's promising, but no-vote for the above reasons.</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-445083-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-445083-1')">1</a>. Edit: There is some backstory (the 'cave') but not enough, for the reasons mentioned later down in this paragraph. Although I think the 'cave' means his cask around his body rather than an actual cave in which he's held, right? Apologies if I'm missing something with this specific aspect.</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
